  <span id="freeText12091824230807307652" style="display:none">The Dalai Lama talks about applying ethics to the new millennium in this book. He bases his ethical system on several Buddhist tenets, but it can apply to everyone.<br /><br />The Dalai Lama notices that people of all creeds and walks of life want the same basic things; an avoidance of pain, happiness, and the same for their children. However, in more advanced societies, this isn't easily accomplished. Wealth doesn't ensure happiness or satisfaction in life.<br /><br />In that vein, The Dalai Lama calls for compassion. If we can understand each other and see people as human beings with problems similar to ours, we can change the world.<br /><br />The Dalai Lama is Tibetan, so the book has phrases in that language. English lacks the subtle differences required to express itself fully.</span>
