        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer211000020" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4832622905600670413">The Dalai Lama is a beautiful, caring, warm soul, one who we can all learn a great deal from. This book is simply his thoughts on what we as individuals can do to make the world a better place, just as the title suggests, in an ever changing world heading into a new Millennium.<br/><br/>There are many great guidelines on these pages, many that our political and social leaders should really take a look at. <br/><br/>There isn&apos;t really anything mind blowing or revolutionary, the ideas are rather basic, but he portray</span>
  <span id="freeText4832622905600670413" style="display:none">The Dalai Lama is a beautiful, caring, warm soul, one who we can all learn a great deal from. This book is simply his thoughts on what we as individuals can do to make the world a better place, just as the title suggests, in an ever changing world heading into a new Millennium.<br /><br />There are many great guidelines on these pages, many that our political and social leaders should really take a look at. <br /><br />There isn't really anything mind blowing or revolutionary, the ideas are rather basic, but he portrays them in such a way as to understand they would be hard to introduce and institute into society, but in the long run they would be worth it.<br /><br />What I liked the best about this book is that it is NOT a religious doctrine. It approaches it's subject in a very Humanist way, accessible and understandable to all people, regardless of religious affiliation.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4832622905600670413" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
